Technical Highlights
Array Canonicalization
Apex allows both String[] and List<String> syntax. For overload resolution, these must be treated equivalently:

func canonicalizeType(typeName string) string {
    if strings.HasSuffix(typeName, "[]") {
        baseType := strings.TrimSuffix(typeName, "[]")
        return "List<" + baseType + ">"
    }
    return typeName
}
Generic Type Matching
Supports covariance for List parameters:

// List<Account> can match List<SObject> parameter
if strings.HasPrefix(argType, "List<") && strings.HasPrefix(paramType, "List<") {
    argElem := extractGenericType(argType)    // "Account"
    paramElem := extractGenericType(paramType) // "SObject"
    if isSubtype(argElem, paramElem) {
        return 500 // Compatible
    }
}
Case-Insensitive Comparison
Apex is case-insensitive, so runtime types (lowercase "string") must match parameter types (capitalized "String"):

argTypeLower := strings.ToLower(argType)
paramTypeLower := strings.ToLower(paramType)
if argTypeLower == paramTypeLower {
    return 1000 // Exact match
}
